organic_results.title: School-enrollment rates and trends, gender, and fertility: A cross-national analysis
organic_results.snippet: London and Hadden (1989) used Thai province-level data to test aspects of Caldwell's" wealth-flows" theory of the decline in fertility, specifically the hypothesis that the spread of education produces declines in fertility. They found strong support for the hypothesis, but could only speculate regarding the degree to which this finding could be generalized beyond the Thai case. This study reports the results of a cross-national analysis (N= 51-59) that assessed the generality of" the spread of education effect." Although only modest …
